Curry can cause food poisoning caused by Welsh bacillus, so if you are making curry, cooling it rapidly and stirring it well to oxygenate it will help prevent the growth of bacteria.

Welsh bacillus food poisoning, which tends to occur on the second day of curry, is easily transmitted from root vegetables, and potatoes should be washed well. Welsh bacillus can be found anywhere, but it seems to be found especially in the soil.

Welsh bacillus food poisoning often causes only minor injuries, but the toxin is not killed by heating, so once it increases, the risk of food poisoning increases. Once you cook anything, you want to eat it as soon as possible.

Temperatures are likely to rise to nearly 30 degrees Celsius today. It looks like it will be easy to get heat stroke if you wear a mask, so you'd better spend some time being aware of it.

Those who are acclimatized to the heat are fine, but those who do not usually sweat, or those who are not acclimatized to the heat and suddenly experience a rise in temperature, should be careful in May and June to avoid heat stroke due to being caught off guard.

Iron is found in liver, scallions, and hijiki, but beef and eggs are the ones that everyone likes and dislikes the least. I heard that iron is not easily absorbed, so I helped with vitamin C.

Women, in particular, are said to be chronically deficient in ferritin (stored iron), which is stocked in the body, so we should be conscious of taking iron. I am usually a proofreading subcontractor. The business was temporarily closed due to Corona, and although I don't have proofreading for that company now, I still felt difficulties during February and May because everyone's words and actions started to become tense and there was no manual for proofreading regarding the pandemic.

We have proofread not only for typographical errors, but also for superlatives and subjective evaluations. In other corporate jobs, I have also secretly corrected worrisome phrases. I thought it would be irritating if a stranger said to me, "Listen, everyone," or "When I was young, I didn't know...

I think it's fine to have feelings in one's mind or to say ah-ha in private, but I think it's scary to transmit them as they are to the general public, especially to leave them in writing. I was taught that "a pen can be a deadly weapon! and I am continuing to study both Japanese grammar and slang.
My phone, which was replaced in May, informs me of the schedule, "May 24-26 Urine". I have no idea what both the dates and keywords mean, and I am puzzled and wondering what they mean.

After checking 3,500 documents in 4 years, I found that men sometimes omit "te-ni-o-ho" and have twisted or supercilious sentences, while women tend to be lazy and long, although their grammar is coherent and easy to read.... Not all of them are like that, but if anything, the meaning is easier to understand for the same gender.

I also think that the readability of a long document is not in good or bad writing, but in the "thoughtfulness" of reading it over and correcting it properly at the end. Chapters that are hard to understand are twisted and misspelled, and you can tell that they were not reviewed at the end, so even if the content is intelligent, it is not gripping.
